ameMeanings":[{"name":"Wood","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: mainly a topographic name for someone who lived in or by a wood, from Middle English <i>wode</i> ‘wood’ (Old English <i>wudu</i>). In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, such as French   Bois   and Polish   Les  .","English: in a few cases, a nickname for an eccentric or perhaps a violent person, from Middle English <i>wode</i> ‘frenzied, wild’ (Old English <i>wōd</i>).","Americanized form of French   Gadbois  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Woode","meanings":["(2007: 216; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Wood  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 312, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]},{"name":"Bois","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alcide, Antoine, Donat, Marcel, Ovide, Ovila, Raoul, Serge.","French: topographic name for someone living or working in a wood, from (Old) French <i>bois</i> ‘wood’ (from Late Latin <i>boscum</i> ‘bush, shrub, undergrowth’, of ancient Germanic origin), or a habitational name from (Le) Bois, the name of several places in various parts of France. This surname is also found in Haiti. Compare   Debois   and the most frequent French form   Dubois  . Compare also   Boie  ,   Boies  , and   Boyce  .","English: variant of   Boyce   and   Boyes  ."]},{"name":"Woods","meanings":["English: variant of   Wood   with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: adopted as a translation of <b>Ó Cuill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Coll</i>’ (see   Quill  ), or in Ulster of <b>Mac Con Coille</b> ‘son of <i>Cú Choille</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘hound of the wood’, which has also been mistranslated   Cox  , as if formed with <i>coileach</i> ‘cock, rooster’."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Nicholas Wood had at least 1 daughter with Nicholas Wood."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1300–1350":"1300–1350","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1300":"1300","1350":"1350","1328":"1328","Harpole, Northamptonshire, England":"Harpole, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1300–1350":"1300–1350","1328–Female":"1328–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1300":"1300","1350":"1350","1328":"1328","Harpole, Northamptonshire, England":"Harpole, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1300–1350":"1300–1350","1328–Female":"1328–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1300":"1300","1350":"1350","1328":"1328","Harpole, Northamptonshire, England":"Harpole, Northamptonshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Nicholas Wood a eu au moins 1 fille avec Nicholas Wood."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","1300–1350":"1300–1350","1328–Female":"1328–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1300":"1300","1350":"1